         <div type="transcription">
            <p>
<lb corresp="#b4"/><w>war</w><w>niset</w><w>yamäṣäle</w><w>sarwana</w><w>likṣale</w>
<w>o<lb corresp="#b5"/>pätsa</w><w>mäskedra</w><pc>॥</pc><foreign xml:lang="san"><w>namo</w><w>prasunnamanasa</w><pc>•</pc><w>mandaviro<milestone unit="w" type="break"/></w></foreign>
<lb corresp="#b6"/><foreign xml:lang="san"><w>-ri</w><w>svaha</w></foreign><w>tesa</w><w>mamanto-pälsko</w><w>takärṣe</w><w>mäsketra</w><pc>•</pc></p>
         </div>
         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#b4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">On water a spell is to be cast. The face is to be washed. She </seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b5"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">becomes not jealous (?). <hi>Sanskrit</hi> </seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b6"><seg><seg type="prim_transl"><hi>Sanskrit</hi> Thereby one who is evil-minded becomes friendly.</seg></seg></choice></p>
         </div>
         <div type="comments">
            <p><note type="lingcomment">The short text shows late/colloquial forms as well as wrong orthography:</note><note type="remarks">The Tocharian text has been written on the blank space after a Sanskrit donor text (ed. in <bibl><title corresp="ref:waldschmidt1965"/><citedRange>83</citedRange></bibl> as no. SHT 146) by a different hand with a brush; the script is very clumsy. 
The leaf comes from the only complete Sanskrit pustaka book unearthed from Qizil, see <bibl><title corresp="ref:sander1994"/><citedRange>98</citedRange></bibl>; <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-tht295"/> and the wooden covers <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-tht3990"/> and <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-tht3990b"/> belong to the same pustaka.</note><note corresp="#b4" type="lingcomment"><hi>sarwana</hi> for <hi>särwāna</hi>;</note><note corresp="#b4" type="philcomment">For the use of the cross-barred square sign to render ‹mä›, see <bibl><title corresp="ref:malzahn2007a"/><citedRange>287</citedRange></bibl>.</note><note corresp="#b4 #b5" type="philcomment">In contrast to <bibl><title corresp="ref:malzahn2007b"/><citedRange>301</citedRange></bibl>, <hi>opätsa</hi> rather seems to be a complete form; <bibl><title corresp="ref:adams2013a"/><citedRange>122</citedRange></bibl> connects it with TA <w lemmaRef="A_päts"/> 'jealousy' and suggests a privative adjective 'not jealous'.</note><note corresp="#b5" type="lingcomment">Skt. <hi>prasunna</hi>- stands for correct Skt.<hi> prasanna</hi>- ‘clear, friendly’, and °<hi>manasa</hi> for genitival °<hi>manasaḥ</hi>, visarga being usually omitted in texts from Eastern Turkestan; note also the use of the genitive instead of the expected dative.</note><note corresp="#b5 #b6" type="lingcomment"><hi>mäsketra</hi> with 3.sg. ending -<hi>ra</hi> but in addition the kind of hypercorrect spelling with <hi>d</hi> in <hi>mäskedra</hi>.</note><note corresp="#b6" type="lingcomment"><hi>mamanto-pälsko</hi> shows late diphthongization; the form seems to be a bahuvrihi compound consisting of the PPt <hi>mamāntau</hi> ‘being evil’ and of <hi>palsko</hi> ‘mind, spirit’. 
Note further that the <hi>Sanskrit</hi> is also corrupt, which is often the case in this pustaka (cf. <bibl><title corresp="ref:sander1994"/></bibl>), esp. with respect to wrong vowels.</note><note corresp="#b6" type="lingcomment"><hi>svaha</hi> for Skt. <hi>svāhā</hi> ‘hail!’.</note></p>
         </div>
