               <item n="m_lingcomment_old">The short text shows late/colloquial forms as well as wrong orthography:&lt;br&gt;
&lt;b&gt;b4&lt;/b&gt; &lt;i&gt;sarwana&lt;/i&gt; for &lt;i&gt;särwāna&lt;/i&gt;;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;b&gt;b5, b6&lt;/b&gt; &lt;i&gt;mäsketra&lt;/i&gt; with 3.sg. ending -&lt;i&gt;ra&lt;/i&gt; but in addition the kind of hypercorrect spelling with &lt;i&gt;d&lt;/i&gt; in &lt;i&gt;mäskedra&lt;/i&gt;.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;b&gt;b6&lt;/b&gt; &lt;i&gt;mamanto-pälsko&lt;/i&gt; shows late diphthongization; the form seems to be a bahuvrihi compound consisting of the PPt &lt;i&gt;mamāntau&lt;/i&gt; ‘being evil’ and of &lt;i&gt;palsko&lt;/i&gt; ‘mind, spirit’.&lt;br&gt;
Note further that the &lt;i&gt;Sanskrit&lt;/i&gt; is also corrupt, which is often the case in this pustaka (cf. [[Sander 1994]]), esp. with respect to wrong vowels.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;b&gt;b5&lt;/b&gt; Skt. &lt;i&gt;prasunna&lt;/i&gt;- stands for correct Skt.&lt;i&gt; prasanna&lt;/i&gt;- ‘clear, friendly’, and °&lt;i&gt;manasa&lt;/i&gt; for genitival °&lt;i&gt;manasaḥ&lt;/i&gt;, visarga being usually omitted in texts from Eastern Turkestan; note also the use of the genitive instead of the expected dative.&lt;br&gt; 
&lt;b&gt;b6&lt;/b&gt; &lt;i&gt;svaha&lt;/i&gt; for Skt. &lt;i&gt;svāhā&lt;/i&gt; ‘hail!’. </item>
